## Vulnerability 2 — POTENTIAL MEDIUM SEVERITY
### `VFSManager.resolveFile()` — No `..` Normalization in VFS Path Resolution
**File:** `src/main/java/org/olat/core/util/vfs/VFSManager.java`
**Used by:** `FolderMapper.java` (line 46)
#### Vulnerable Code — VFSManager (lines 170–213)
```java
public static VFSItem resolveFile(VFSContainer rootContainer, String path) {
path = VFSManager.sanitizePath(path);    // Only trims trailing slash / adds leading slash
if (path.equals("/")) { return rootContainer; }
if (rootContainer instanceof LocalFolderImpl) {
String childName = extractChild(path);          // Extracts first path segment — CAN BE ".."
LocalFolderImpl l = (LocalFolderImpl) rootContainer;
File t = new File(l.getBasefile().getAbsolutePath(), childName);  // new File(base, "..") = PARENT DIR
if (t.exists()) {
if (t.isDirectory()) {
VFSContainer subContainer = new LocalFolderImpl(t, rootContainer);
String subPath = path.substring(childName.length() + 1);
return resolveFile(subContainer, subPath);   // Recursion continues OUTSIDE base dir
} else {
return new LocalFileImpl(t, rootContainer);
}
} else {
return null;
}
}
// ...
}
```
#### Root Cause Analysis
- `sanitizePath()` only normalizes the leading/trailing slash. It does **not** remove or reject `..` segments.
- `extractChild()` returns the first path component verbatim; if the path is `/../etc/passwd`, it returns `..`.
- `new File(baseDir, "..")` resolves to the parent directory of `baseDir`.
- The recursion then continues into the parent directory, effectively escaping the intended VFS root.
#### Used by `FolderMapper` (line 46)
```java
public MediaResource handle(String relPath, HttpServletRequest request) {
VFSItem vfsItem = container.resolve(relPath);   // relPath is user-supplied
CmdServeResource cmdResource = new CmdServeResource();
return cmdResource.getMediaResource(relPath, vfsItem);
}
```
The exploitability of this path depends on whether the `relPath` arriving at `FolderMapper.handle()` is URL-decoded and unfiltered from user input, or if it goes through an earlier sanitization layer (e.g., the mapper dispatch framework). The VFS layer itself offers no protection.
#### Severity: **MEDIUM** (conditional on caller context)
