### Vulnerability 2 — HIGH: `Connection` Not Closed on Exception in `runInTransaction` (both overloads)
**File:** `core/src/main/java/org/sql2o/Sql2o.java`
**Lines:** 373–385 and 396–408
**First overload (`StatementRunnable`, lines 373–385):**
```java
public void runInTransaction(StatementRunnable runnable, Object argument, int isolationLevel){
Connection connection = this.beginTransaction(isolationLevel);
connection.setRollbackOnException(false);
try {
runnable.run(connection, argument);
} catch (Throwable throwable) {
connection.rollback();    // ← rollback(true) closes connection
throw new Sql2oException(...);
}
connection.commit();          // ← commit(true) closes connection
}
```
**Second overload (`StatementRunnableWithResult`, lines 396–408):**
```java
public <V> V runInTransaction(StatementRunnableWithResult<V> runnableWithResult, Object argument, int isolationLevel){
Connection connection = this.beginTransaction(isolationLevel);
Object result;
try{
result = runnableWithResult.run(connection, argument);
} catch (Throwable throwable) {
connection.rollback();    // ← rollback(true) closes connection
throw new Sql2oException(...);
}
connection.commit();          // ← commit(true) closes connection
return (V)result;
}
```
**The problem:** Both `connection.rollback()` (which calls `rollback(true)`) and `connection.commit()` (which calls `commit(true)`) internally close the JDBC connection. **However**, if `connection.commit()` itself throws a `Sql2oException` (lines 159–161 in Connection.java re-throw), the `commit(true)` will still call `closeJdbcConnection()` in its `finally` block — so this path is actually safe.
**However**, a more subtle issue: `connection.rollback()` on line 381 only calls `rollback(true)`, which calls `closeJdbcConnection()` in the `finally`. But if `rollback()` itself throws (which is caught and only logged as a warning — line 143), and then the exception re-throw on line 382 propagates without closing, the connection may not be closed if `closeJdbcConnection()` was skipped. This is partially mitigated by the `finally` in `rollback(boolean)`, but the Connection object itself has no enclosing `finally` or `try-with-resources` in `runInTransaction`. If the `beginTransaction()` call partially succeeds but the exception path is unusual, the connection could leak.
More concretely: there is **no `finally` block** wrapping the connection in either `runInTransaction` method. This contrasts with `withConnection` (lines 218–230) which correctly uses a `finally` block. If `connection.commit()` throws an exception before `closeJdbcConnection()` is invoked inside `commit(boolean)`, the connection escapes.

