## Vulnerability 3 — `progressive-text.js` assigns raw server response to `innerHTML` (HIGH)
**File:** `core/src/main/resources/lib/hudson/progressive-text.js:68`
```javascript
rsp.text().then((responseText) => {
var text = responseText;
if (text !== "") {
var p = document.createElement("DIV");
e.appendChild(p);
p.innerHTML = text;   // ← raw server response
```
This is the **console output streaming** feature. The server response (build console logs) is injected directly into the DOM via `innerHTML`. Jenkins annotates console output with HTML (via `ConsoleAnnotator`), so this is by design — but any failure to sanitize annotator output server-side flows directly to the browser as executable HTML.
**CWE-079 type:** Stored XSS (if console output contains unsanitized user-controlled data)

4
## Vulnerability 4 — `textarea.js` previews user-entered markup via `innerHTML` (HIGH)
**File:** `core/src/main/resources/lib/form/textarea/textarea.js:86`
```javascript
var render = function (txt) {
previewDiv.innerHTML = txt;   // ← server-rendered markup
...
};
fetch(rootURL + showPreview.getAttribute("previewEndpoint"), {
method: "post",
body: new URLSearchParams({ text: text }),  // ← user input
})
.then((rsp) => rsp.text().then((responseText) => { ... render(responseText) ... }));
```
The user's description text is POSTed to `MarkupFormatter.doPreviewDescription()`, which calls `translate(text, w)` and returns the result as HTML, which is then assigned to `previewDiv.innerHTML`.
**The risk:** If a `MarkupFormatter` implementation does not properly sanitize markup (e.g., a wiki-markup plugin that passes through some HTML), XSS is achievable. The base class adds CSP headers (`default-src 'none'`) when `PREVIEWS_SET_CSP=true` (default), which **mitigates but does not fully prevent** this — inline scripts from the preview HTML would be blocked, but HTML injection (e.g., exfiltration via CSS, `<form>` injection) remains possible.
**CWE-079 type:** Reflected XSS (in preview context, CSP-partially-mitigated)

