### Vulnerability 2 — **CONFIRMED MEDIUM** | `MagickCore/draw.c: ClonePolygonEdgesTLS()`
**File:** `MagickCore/draw.c`, lines 4740–4793
This function clones polygon edge data across multiple TLS (thread-local storage) slots for parallel rendering. It performs a three-level nested allocation: `polygon_info[i]` → `edges` array → per-edge `points` array. On each inner failure, it returns `MagickFalse` without freeing the partially constructed data for the **current** slot `i`, nor any **previously completed** slots.
#### Level 1 — `polygon_info[i]` allocation (line 4754):
```c
polygon_info[i]=(PolygonInfo *) AcquireMagickMemory(sizeof(*polygon_info[i]));
if (polygon_info[i] == (PolygonInfo *) NULL)
{
(void) ThrowMagickException(..., "MemoryAllocationFailed",...);
return(MagickFalse);   // ✓ nothing allocated yet for slot i — safe
}
```
*(Safe for slot `i`, but all previously completed slots `0..i-1` are orphaned if the caller does not clean up.)*
#### Level 2 — `edges` array allocation (line 4764):
```c
polygon_info[i]->edges=(EdgeInfo *) AcquireQuantumMemory(
polygon_info[0]->number_edges,sizeof(*edge_info));
if (polygon_info[i]->edges == (EdgeInfo *) NULL)
{
(void) ThrowMagickException(..., "MemoryAllocationFailed",...);
return(MagickFalse);
// ✗ polygon_info[i] (the PolygonInfo struct itself) is NOT freed
}
```
#### Level 3 — per-edge `points` allocation (line 4780):
```c
polygon_info[i]->edges[j].points=(PointInfo *) AcquireQuantumMemory(
edge_info->number_points,sizeof(*edge_info));
if (polygon_info[i]->edges[j].points == (PointInfo *) NULL)
{
(void) ThrowMagickException(..., "MemoryAllocationFailed",...);
return(MagickFalse);
// ✗ polygon_info[i] (struct) NOT freed
// ✗ polygon_info[i]->edges (array) NOT freed
// ✗ all points[0..j-1] already allocated in this loop NOT freed
}
```
**Impact:** Under memory pressure during multi-threaded rendering of complex vector drawings (SVG, MVG), this function can fail partway through, leaking `O(number_threads × number_edges)` memory per failed draw call. The caller `AcquirePolygonTLS` (line 4704) calls `DestroyPolygonTLS` only on its own errors, not on `ClonePolygonEdgesTLS` failures — the returned `MagickFalse` leaves the partially-filled `polygon_info` array in an inconsistent, partially-freed state.

